description: The data file provides detailed information on the measles outbreak in the United States during 2025. As of November 4, 2025, there were 1,681 confirmed cases reported across 42 jurisdictions, including Texas, South Carolina, and Utah. The outbreak is significant, with 44 outbreaks reported, and 87% of cases being outbreak-associated. The majority of cases involve unvaccinated individuals, with 92% having unknown or no vaccination status. The data highlights the importance of vaccination, as the outbreak has led to hospitalizations and three confirmed deaths.

The data file documents a measles outbreak in Minnesota during 2025, with 18 confirmed cases reported by October 1st. The outbreak primarily affects unvaccinated individuals in the Twin Cities metro area, linked to domestic and international travel. The Minnesota Department of Health emphasizes the importance of immunization, particularly the measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine, to prevent further spread. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) notes a significant rise in measles cases nationwide, with over 1,500 cases in 2025, marking the highest count since 1992.

The data file details a significant measles outbreak in the United States during 2025. As of November 4, 2025, there were 1,681 confirmed cases across 42 jurisdictions, including Texas, New Mexico, and Ohio, with 44 outbreaks reported. The outbreak was particularly severe in Texas, with 803 cases. The majority of cases were among unvaccinated individuals, and there were three confirmed deaths. This outbreak represents a substantial increase compared to previous years, highlighting the importance of vaccination and public health interventions. The data underscores the ongoing challenges in controlling measles due to declining vaccination rates.

The data file provides information on the monkeypox outbreak, focusing on clade I and clade II variants. The outbreak is primarily affecting Central and Eastern Africa, with clade I cases reported in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and neighboring countries. The data spans from 2022 to 2025, highlighting the ongoing global spread and public health responses, including vaccination efforts and wastewater surveillance for early detection.

This data file provides an analysis of media coverage during the 2025 measles outbreak in the United States, which saw the highest number of cases since the disease was declared eliminated in 2000. The findings highlight gaps in evidence-based reporting and opportunities for improved health communication.

The file also includes guidelines for managing measles cases and outbreaks, emphasizing the importance of accurate diagnosis and vaccination.
